==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wound
<hw>Wound</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>wounde</ets>, <ets>wunde</ets>, AS. <ets>wund</ets>; akin to
OFries. <ets>wunde</ets>, OS. <ets>wunda</ets>, D. <ets>wonde</ets>,
OHG. <ets>wunta</ets>, G. <ets>wunde</ets>, Icel. <ets>und</ets>, and to
AS., OS., & G. <ets>wund</ets> sore, wounded, OHG. <ets>wunt</ets>,
Goth. <ets>wunds</ets>, and perhaps also to Goth. <ets>winnan</ets> to
suffer, E. <ets>win</ets>. ⟦root⟧140. Cf. Zounds.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A hurt or injury caused by violence; specifically, a
breach of the skin and flesh of an animal, or in the substance of any
creature or living thing; a cut, stab, rent, or the like.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Showers of blood⟦br⟧
Rained from the <qex>wounds</qex> of slaughtered Englishmen.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: An injury, hurt, damage, detriment, or the
like, to feeling, faculty, reputation, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Criminal Law)</fld> <def>An injury to the person by
which the skin is divided, or its continuity broken; a lesion of the
body, involving some solution of continuity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ Walker condemns the pronunciation <xex>woond</xex> as a
⟦ldquo⟧capricious novelty.⟦rdquo⟧ It is certainly opposed to an
important principle of our language, namely, that the Old English long
sound written <xex>ou</xex>, and pronounced like French <xex>ou</xex> or
modern English <xex>oo</xex>, has regularly changed, when accented, into
the diphthongal sound usually written with the same letters
<xex>ou</xex> in modern English, as in <xex>ground</xex>,
<xex>hound</xex>, <xex>round</xex>, <xex>sound</xex>. The use of
<xex>ou</xex> in Old English to represent the sound of modern English
<xex>oo</xex> was borrowed from the French, and replaced the older and
Anglo-Saxon spelling with <xex>u</xex>. It makes no difference whether
the word was taken from the French or not, provided it is old enough in
English to have suffered this change to what is now the common sound of
<xex>ou</xex>; but words taken from the French at a later time, or
influenced by French, may have the French sound.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Wound gall</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>an elongated
swollen or tuberous gall on the branches of the grapevine, caused by a
small reddish brown weevil (<spn>Ampeloglypter sesostris</spn>) whose
larvae inhabit the galls.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wound</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Wound
<hw>Wound</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Wounded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wounding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[AS. <ets>wundian</ets>.
⟦root⟧140. See <er>Wound</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To hurt by violence; to produce a breach, or
separation of parts, in, as by a cut, stab, blow, or the like.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The archers hit him; and he was sore <qex>wounded</qex> of the
archers.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam. xxxi. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To hurt the feelings of; to pain by disrespect,
ingratitude, or the like; to cause injury to.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When ye sin so against the brethren, and <qex>wound</qex> their
weak conscience, ye sin against Christ.</q> <rj><qau>1 Cor. viii.
12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Woundable</ent>⟦br⟧
